                        <p>Skincare <a href="theordinary-toners" style="color:#757575"><u>toners</u></a> have come a long way in recent years. While some still contain alcohol, today’s formulations are far more balanced—moving away from the astringent-heavy approach of the past. These products were traditionally meant to combat excessive oil and enlarged pores but often left skin feeling dried out.</p> <p>Nowadays, <b>toners</b> have a much gentler format and have taken on a whole new role. As part of the Prep stage in a daily regimen (more on this below), <b>toners</b> help prepare the skin for additional products like <a href="theordinary-serums" style="color:#757575"><u>serums</u></a>, <a href="theordinary-faceoils" style="color:#757575"><u>face oils</u></a>, and <a href="theordinary-moisturizers" style="color:#757575"><u>moisturizers</u></a>.</p> <p>Still, <b>toners</b> are often overlooked, and many wonder if they're essential to their skincare toolkit. To find out, let's examine what a <b>skin toner</b> is used for and the benefits of using one. </p>
